The function 'localtime()', and given a 'time_t' value, it will break out the date and time into the fields of a 'tm' structure. 
	Here's the code to call it: 
		push OldTime		; Push address of calendar time value
		call localtime		; Return pointer to static time sturture in eax
		add esp, 4		; Stack cleanup for 1 parm

Here, 'oldTime' is a 'time_t' value.
Given this value, 'localtime()' returns in EAX much in the manner of 'ctime()' apointer to a 'tm' structure within the C library somewhere. 
By using this pointer as a base address, you can access the fields in the structure. 
That trick lies in knowing the offset into 'tm' for the individual time/date field that you want, and using that offset as a constant displacement from the address base. 
THe code below displays the year field from a 'tm' structure to the console using 'printf'. 
Note that the first instruction indexes into 'tm' by 20 bytes, which is the offset of the year field from the beginning of the structure: 
		mov edx, dword [eax+20]	; Year value is 20 bytes offset into tm
		push edx		; Push value onto the stack 	
		push yrmsg		; Push address of base string 
		call printf		; Display string and year value with printf
		add esp, byte 8		; Stack cleanup: 2 parms X 4 bytes = 8

By using the displacements shown you can access all the other components of the time and the date in the 'tm' structure, each stored as 32-bit integer value.
